g -- tThe Origins of the LUGAL Office -- tUps and Downs in the Career of Enmerkar, King of Uruk -- t“Šulgi, Mighty Man, King of Ur” -- tThe Fate of Yasmaḫ-Addu, the King of Mari -- tFinding the Good Genius in Your Bowl -- tThe Royal Adoption Scene in Ugaritic and Biblical Texts -- t“One Epic or Many?” Das Tukultī-Ninurta-Epos zum Ersten, zum Zweiten und zum. . .? -- tPart 4 City and State -- tClimate Change, the Mardu Wall, and the Fall of Ur -- tRegional Differences in Middle Assyrian -- tThe Anatolian and Iranian Frontiers: Analyzing the Foreign Policy of the Assyrian Empire under Esarhaddon -- tFinis Assyriae: The Fall of the Assyrian State, or the Fall of the Assyrian Civilisation? -- tFortune and Politics: Nabopolassar’s Campaigns in 616–615 b.c.e. and His Alliance with Media -- tMore about the Crisis in Uruk -- tPart 5 God and Temple -- tDon’t Insult Inana! Divine Retribution for Offense against Common Decency in the Light of New Textual Sources -- tFortune and Misfortune of the Eagle in the Myth of Etana -- tWithin the Ekur: Sitz im Leben for a Literary Topos Regarding Nintur -- tSome Remarks on the Archaeology of the Ekur of Nippur during Post-Kassite Times0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the week between July 21 and 25, 2014, the University of Warsaw hosted more than three hundred Assyriologists from all over the world. In the course of five days, nearly 150 papers were read in three (and sometimes four) parallel sessions. Many of them were delivered within the framework of nine thematic workshops. The publication of most of these panels is underway, in separate volumes. As is usually the case, the academic sessions were accompanied by many opportunities for social interaction among the participants, and there was time to enjoy the historical and cultural benefits of Warsaw. Special honor was accorded to two American Assyriologists whose origins can be traced to Warsaw, Piotr Michalowski and Piotr Steinkeller, and a special session to recognize their contributions to the study of ancient Mesopotamia was organized. In this book are presented papers on the main theme of the meeting, “Fortune and Misfortune in the Ancient Near East.”&#157; The 31 essays are organized into 5 sections: (1) plenary presenations on “What Is Fortune? What Is Misfortune?”&#157; (2) humanity and fortune/misfortune and luck, with discussion of specific examples; (3) additional papers on definitions of fortune and misfortune; (4) the effects on city and state; and (5) God and temple.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAssyriologiexCongrès. 0aAssyriologyvCongresses. 0aAssyriologyxCongresses. 0aChancexCongrèsxHistoirexMachreqxMiddle EastxHistoryxConference papers and proceedings. 0aCivilisation assyro-babyloniennexCongrès. 0aCivilization, Assyro-BabylonianvCongresses. 0aCivilization, Assyro-BabylonianxCongresses. 0aFortunexCongressesxHistoryxMiddle East. 0aFortunezMiddle EastxHistoryvCongresses. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh1 aAbusch, Tzvi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAvila, Mark A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeckman, Gary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBilgin, Tayfun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonneterre, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCharvát, Petr, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrewnowska, Olga, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDromard, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerruh Adalı, Selim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relato